  <content>
    <title>Influencer Marketing</title>

Four-phase influencer framework: discover micro-influencers (10K–100K) by engagement quality, vet for audience match and fraud signals, personalized outreach, FTC-compliant disclosures, track ROI via unique discount codes.

    <why>
      <p>Most influencer campaigns fail because brands select by follower count, produce inauthentic briefs, and skip attribution setup. Micro-influencers at 10K–100K deliver the best ROI for niche products: high trust, lower cost, and real engagement. Engagement-rate gating (above platform averages) eliminates inflated accounts before budget is spent.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Reaching new audiences when SEO and paid ads have plateaued or have unfavorable unit economics.</item>
        <item>Launching a product to a niche where 10K–100K creators drive purchase decisions (DTC, SaaS prosumer, creator tools).</item>
        <item>Building a UGC pipeline cheaply via gifting + reuse rights instead of in-house production.</item>
        <item>Pre-launch seeding: placing product with micro creators in target niche to generate D-day content.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>B2B enterprise (ACV above $10K) where buying committees ignore creator endorsements.</item>
        <item>Highly regulated verticals (medical, financial advice, securities) — FTC + sector compliance rules are brittle.</item>
        <item>Marketing budgets under $5K — fixed costs of vetting, outreach, and contracts erode ROI; start with referral programs instead.</item>
        <item>Products with no demonstrable 30-second hero moment — creators cannot make compelling content.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="influencer-tiers">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Start with micro-influencers (10K–100K followers). They deliver the best ROI for most brands: high audience trust, lower cost, accessible for outreach, and real engagement. Scale to mid or macro only after proving unit economics on micro.</statement>
        <rationale>Macro influencers have large reach but lower engagement rates and high cost. Micro-influencers in a specific niche have audiences that trust them as peers, not as celebrities — critical for purchase decisions in prosumer and SaaS products.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <p>Tier reference: Nano (1K–10K, high engagement, limited reach), Micro (10K–100K, best ROI starting point), Mid (100K–500K, good reach but higher cost), Macro (500K–1M, expensive), Mega (1M+, very expensive, less engaged).</p>
    </section>

    <section name="vetting-criteria">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Gate every candidate on engagement rate before any other evaluation. Below-average engagement for the platform is disqualifying regardless of follower count.</statement>
        <rationale>Follower count can be purchased; engagement cannot be faked at scale without detection. A 100K-follower account with 0.8% engagement has a smaller real audience than a 20K-follower account with 4% engagement.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <p>Engagement rate benchmarks: Instagram good 2–3% / great 4%+; TikTok good 3–5% / great 8%+; Twitter/X good 1–2% / great 3%+; YouTube good 2–4% / great 5%+.</p>
      <p>Evaluation criteria weights: audience match (30%), engagement rate (25%), content quality (20%), brand safety (15%), professionalism/reliability (10%).</p>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Flag and reject any candidate with: a sudden follower spike in the past 30 days, engagement rate below platform good-threshold, generic bot-pattern comments ("Nice post!", single emoji), or more than 30% sponsored content in the last 30 posts.</statement>
        <rationale>These are reliable signals of purchased followers or audience burnout. Paying for reach that doesn't exist produces zero conversions regardless of brief quality.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="discovery-methods">
      <p>Manual: search relevant hashtags, look at who your existing customers follow, check competitor collaboration credits.</p>
      <p>Tools: Modash, HypeAuditor, Upfluence for discovery and fraud detection; BuzzSumo for content creators; SparkToro for audience research.</p>
      <p>Outbound: Twitter/X bio search for niche terms, YouTube channel search, newsletter directories.</p>
      <reference path="templates/score-creator.py">Creator scoring script: engagement rate + audience match + niche fit + content quality; flags suspect accounts</reference>
    </section>

    <section name="outreach">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Reference a specific recent post by URL in every outreach message. Generic "I love your work on [TOPIC]" openers are flagged as mass outreach and ignored. Include a specific line from their content and explain why it resonated.</statement>
        <rationale>Creators receive dozens of generic pitches daily. Proof of genuine engagement raises response rates 3–5x over templated outreach. Platform DM algorithms also rate-limit accounts sending identical messages.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Do not send outreach DMs autonomously via agent. Instagram and TikTok shadow-ban accounts exceeding ~50 DMs per day. Queue outreach for human confirmation before sending.</statement>
        <rationale>Platform anti-spam systems cannot distinguish AI-bulk outreach from legitimate outreach. Account shadow-banning eliminates the brand's ability to reach any creator on that platform, not just the flagged campaign.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="compensation-models">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>For unproven creators, start with an affiliate + gifting hybrid. Convert top performers (with 60 days of data) to flat-fee retainers.</statement>
        <rationale>Hybrid compensation aligns incentives — creators earn more when they drive results. Flat fees without performance data create risk: you are paying for reach that may not convert.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <p>Compensation models: gifting (product awareness, free product), flat fee (specific deliverables), affiliate (commission per sale, performance-based), revenue share (% ongoing for long-term), hybrid (flat + affiliate).</p>
      <p>Approximate rate benchmarks (Instagram post / YouTube video): Nano $50–250 / $200–500; Micro $250–1K / $500–2K; Mid $1K–5K / $2K–10K; Macro $5K–25K / $10K–50K.</p>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Negotiate UGC reuse rights upfront: "90-day paid-social usage rights." Creator content reused in Meta/TikTok ads delivers 3–5x ROAS because it carries authentic social proof signals that native-brand ads lack.</statement>
        <rationale>UGC rights are cheapest to acquire during the original negotiation. Post-campaign rights requests are often refused or priced at 2–5x the original content fee.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="ftc-compliance">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Every campaign brief must state: "All posts must include #ad or #sponsored in the first three hashtags or in visible text above the fold." Verify this in the post before and after go-live.</statement>
        <rationale>FTC Endorsement Guides require clear and conspicuous disclosure. #ad buried in 30 hashtags or disclosed only in caption overflow does not meet the "conspicuous" standard. Non-compliance creates FTC investigation risk for both brand and creator.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <reference path="templates/campaign-brief.md">Campaign brief template including FTC disclosure requirement and approval process</reference>
    </section>

    <section name="attribution">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Assign a unique discount code per creator (e.g., SARAH15). Codes survive iOS 14.5 tracking loss and cookie deprecation, provide clear per-creator attribution, and double as a customer incentive.</statement>
        <rationale>UTM links break when users navigate between apps or share links. A creator-specific code is the most reliable cross-channel attribution signal available without third-party SDKs.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <reference path="templates/tracking-sheet.md">Influencer tracking spreadsheet template</reference>
    </section>

    <section name="key-metrics">
      <p>Metrics and targets: Reach (audience exposure, goal-dependent), Engagement rate (content resonance, above platform average), Click-through (interest signal, above 1%), Conversions (business impact, goal-dependent), CPM (cost efficiency, below $20), ROI (overall return, above 2x).</p>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Focus on conversions and ROI as primary metrics, not reach and impressions. "2M impressions" with zero conversions means audience did not match ICP.</statement>
        <rationale>Vanity reach metrics inflate program perception but do not reflect business value. A 230K-reach campaign that produced 130 conversions outperforms a 2M-reach campaign with 20 conversions at any LTV.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <reference path="templates/campaign-report.md">Post-campaign report template with per-influencer and summary metrics</reference>
    </section>

    <section name="case-examples">
      <example type="good" title="SaaS product launch">
        <note>SaaS product launch: 10 micro-influencers in productivity niche, YouTube video reviews, affiliate codes. Budget $15,000. Results: 800K total reach, 620 trial signups, $24 cost per acquisition, 2.5x ROI factoring LTV. Key driver: YouTube format enables extended demos that drive qualified signups.</note>
      </example>
      <example type="good" title="E-commerce product launch">
        <note>E-commerce product: 50 nano/micro Instagram influencers, gifting + affiliate (10% commission), UGC reuse rights negotiated. Budget $5,000 (product + fees). Results: 2M impressions, $75K in attributed sales, 15x ROI. Key driver: gifting hybrid + UGC reuse in paid ads amplified reach without proportional spend.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="ai-agent-gotchas">
      <antipattern>
        <description>LLMs hallucinate engagement rates and follower counts when asked to "check" a creator.</description>
        <reason>Models have no real-time data. Always pull live data via API (Modash, HypeAuditor) or scraping. Never trust a model's asserted metrics.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent-generated personalization produces generic patterns even when prompted for specificity ("I love your work on [TOPIC]").</description>
        <reason>Require the agent to quote a specific post URL and a specific line from that post. Generic pattern outputs are worse than no outreach — they create negative brand impressions.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Skipping brand-safety filtering before approving a creator for outreach.</description>
        <reason>Scan last 30 post captions for political, NSFW, or controversy-adjacent terms before any outreach or content approval. One brand-safety incident can override a full quarter of positive campaign results.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Quoting USD-only rates to creators in India, Brazil, or the Philippines without local-currency equivalent.</description>
        <reason>Mismatched expectations from currency confusion break deals. Agents should output both USD and local currency for any creator outside the US, EU, or UK.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/campaign-brief.md" purpose="Campaign brief: brand, deliverables, creative guidelines, FTC disclosure requirements, compensation"/>
      <template path="templates/tracking-sheet.md" purpose="Influencer tracking spreadsheet: handle, platform, followers, ER, niche, status, rate"/>
      <template path="templates/campaign-report.md" purpose="Post-campaign report: per-influencer metrics, results vs. goals, top-performing content, learnings"/>
      <template path="templates/score-creator.py" purpose="Creator scoring: engagement rate + audience match + niche fit + content quality, flags suspect accounts"/>
    </templates>

